The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Delhi stuck with crime tag

 New Delhi, Sept. 3 (PTI): Delhi continues to be the most unsafe place in India for women.

 In 2005, it recorded the highest rate of crime against women at 27.6 per cent, compared to the national average of 14.1 per cent.

 The report by the National Crime Records Bureau (NCRB) includes crimes such as rape, dowry-related deaths, molestation and incest. 

 Delhi is followed by Andhra Pradesh, which reported 26.1 per cent of such crimes.

 Noting that one IPC crime is reported every 17 seconds in the country, NCRBs Crime Clock-2005 said one crime was committed against women every three minutes and one molestation every 15 minutes.

 One rape was reported every 29 minutes and one sexual harassment case every 53 minutes, the report said.

 Among the 35 megacities in the country those having a population of more than 10 lakh and above Delhi alone reported 33.2 per cent (562) of the total 1,693 rape cases.

 Out of 2,409 kidnappings of women, Delhi recorded 37.4 per cent or 900 cases, the report said.

 Delhi has also topped the list of crime against children with 6.5 per cent as compared to the national average of 1.4 per cent, NCRB said. 

 A total of 1,55,553 crimes against women were reported in the country in 2005 a marginal increase of 0.8 per cent over the 1,54,333 crimes during 2004.

 While one murder was reported every 16 minutes, one crime was committed against children every 35 minutes. One burglary case was recorded every six minutes and one theft every two minutes.

 According to the report, 50,26,337 cognisable crimes, 18,22,602 under IPC and 32,03,735 under special and local laws were reported in 2005, a decline of 16.6 per cent over a total of 60,28,781 cases in 2004.




